---
import Layout from '../../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Repl from '../../../../components/Repl';
import SchemeRepl from '../../../../components/SchemeRepl';
import Neighbors from "../../../../components/Neighbors.astro";
import PrevNext from "../../../../components/PrevNext.astro";
---

<Layout title="Econ Ch.17 — Interest and Time Value" favicon="💰">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/economics/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to economics</a>

    <h1>Interest and Time Value</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Sources: Wikipedia (CC BY-SA 4.0) · Adam Smith, <em>Wealth of Nations</em> (1776, public domain)</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A dollar today is worth more than a dollar tomorrow. <strong>Compound interest</strong> turns this intuition into arithmetic: future value grows exponentially, present value shrinks by discounting. Every investment decision reduces to comparing present values.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Compound Interest -->
    <h3>Compound interest</h3>
    <p>If you invest principal P at annual rate r, compounded once per year, after t years you have FV = P(1 + r)<sup>t</sup>. Compounding more frequently (n times per year) gives FV = P(1 + r/n)<sup>nt</sup>. As n approaches infinity, you get continuous compounding: FV = Pe<sup>rt</sup>.</p>

    <!-- SVG: Compound growth curve -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 400 250" class="w-full max-w-md" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Axes -->
        <line x1="50" y1="200" x2="370" y2="200" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
        <line x1="50" y1="200" x2="50" y2="30" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
        <text x="210" y="230" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.6">Years</text>
        <text x="20" y="115" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.6" transform="rotate(-90,20,115)">Value</text>
        <!-- Grid lines -->
        <line x1="50" y1="160" x2="370" y2="160" stroke="#71717a" stroke-width="0.5" stroke-opacity="0.45"/>
        <line x1="50" y1="120" x2="370" y2="120" stroke="#71717a" stroke-width="0.5" stroke-opacity="0.45"/>
        <line x1="50" y1="80" x2="370" y2="80" stroke="#71717a" stroke-width="0.5" stroke-opacity="0.45"/>
        <!-- Simple interest (linear) -->
        <line x1="50" y1="180" x2="370" y2="100" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.3" stroke-dasharray="5,3"/>
        <text x="372" y="100" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">simple</text>
        <!-- Compound interest (exponential curve, 7% over 30 years) -->
        <path d="M 50 180 Q 130 170 180 155 Q 230 135 270 105 Q 310 70 350 35" fill="none" stroke="#4ade80" stroke-width="2"/>
        <text x="352" y="35" fill="#4ade80" font-size="10">compound</text>
        <!-- Labels -->
        <text x="50" y="195" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.5">0</text>
        <text x="210" y="215" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.5">15</text>
        <text x="370" y="215" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.5">30</text>
        <text x="45" y="183" text-anchor="end" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.5">P</text>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Compound interest: FV = P * (1 + r)^t
; P = principal, r = annual rate, t = years

(define (future-value P r t)
  (* P (expt (+ 1 r) t)))

; $1000 at 7% for 10, 20, 30 years
(display "10 years: $")
(display (round (future-value 1000 0.07 10))) (newline)
(display "20 years: $")
(display (round (future-value 1000 0.07 20))) (newline)
(display "30 years: $")
(display (round (future-value 1000 0.07 30))) (newline)

; Rule of 72: doubling time ~ 72/r
(display "Rule of 72 doubling time at 7%: ")
(display (/ 72 7))
(display " years")
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Compound interest
def future_value(P, r, t):
    return P * (1 + r) ** t

for t in [10, 20, 30]:
    fv = future_value(1000, 0.07, t)
    print(str(t) + " years: $" + str(round(fv)))

# Rule of 72
print("Rule of 72 doubling time at 7%: " + str(round(72/7, 1)) + " years")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 2. Present Value and Discounting -->
    <h3>Present value and discounting</h3>
    <p>Present value reverses the direction: PV = FV / (1 + r)<sup>t</sup>. The discount rate r encodes your opportunity cost. A dollar arriving in 10 years at 7% discount is worth only $0.51 today. This is the foundation of all valuation.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Present value: PV = FV / (1 + r)^t

(define (present-value FV r t)
  (/ FV (expt (+ 1 r) t)))

; What is $1000 received in 10 years worth today?
(display "PV of $1000 in 10 years at 7%: $")
(display (round (present-value 1000 0.07 10))) (newline)

(display "PV of $1000 in 20 years at 7%: $")
(display (round (present-value 1000 0.07 20))) (newline)

; Higher discount rate = lower present value
(display "PV of $1000 in 10 years at 12%: $")
(display (round (present-value 1000 0.12 10)))
`} />


    <!-- 3. Net Present Value -->
    <h3>Net present value</h3>
    <p>NPV sums the present values of all future cash flows, minus the initial investment. If NPV is greater than zero, the project creates value. NPV is additive: two independent projects can be evaluated separately.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; NPV = sum of discounted cash flows - initial cost
; Cash flows: list of (year . amount) pairs

(define (present-value FV r t)
  (/ FV (expt (+ 1 r) t)))

(define (npv rate initial-cost cash-flows)
  (define (sum-pv flows)
    (if (null? flows)
        0
        (+ (present-value (cdar flows) rate (caar flows))
           (sum-pv (cdr flows)))))
  (- (sum-pv cash-flows) initial-cost))

; Project: costs $5000 upfront, returns $2000/year for 3 years
(define flows (list (cons 1 2000) (cons 2 2000) (cons 3 2000)))

(display "NPV at 5%: $")
(display (round (npv 0.05 5000 flows))) (newline)
(display "NPV at 15%: $")
(display (round (npv 0.15 5000 flows)))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Net present value
def npv(rate, initial_cost, cash_flows):
    pv_sum = sum(cf / (1 + rate)**t for t, cf in cash_flows)
    return pv_sum - initial_cost

# Project: $5000 upfront, $2000/year for 3 years
flows = [(1, 2000), (2, 2000), (3, 2000)]

print("NPV at 5%: $" + str(round(npv(0.05, 5000, flows), 2)))
print("NPV at 15%: $" + str(round(npv(0.15, 5000, flows), 2)))
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 4. Annuities -->
    <h3>Annuities</h3>
    <p>An annuity is a fixed payment C repeated for n periods. The present value of an annuity has a closed form: PV = C * (1 - (1+r)<sup>-n</sup>) / r. Mortgages, bonds, and pensions are all annuities in disguise. The connection to integrals: a continuous annuity is the integral of Ce<sup>-rt</sup> from 0 to T.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Annuity PV = C * (1 - (1+r)^(-n)) / r
; C = payment per period, r = rate, n = periods

(define (annuity-pv C r n)
  (* C (/ (- 1 (expt (+ 1 r) (- n))) r)))

; $500/month for 30 years at 6% annual (0.5% monthly)
(define monthly-pv (annuity-pv 500 0.005 360))
(display "PV of $500/month for 30 years: $")
(display (round monthly-pv)) (newline)

; Mortgage: what monthly payment for $300,000 loan?
; C = PV * r / (1 - (1+r)^(-n))
(define (mortgage-payment PV r n)
  (* PV (/ r (- 1 (expt (+ 1 r) (- n))))))

(define pmt (mortgage-payment 300000 0.005 360))
(display "Monthly payment on $300k mortgage: $")
(display (round pmt))
`} />


